"1165":"1165","1220":"1220","Bef October 1181":"vóór oktober 1181","1130":"1130","1181":"1181","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Bef 1133–Bef October 1181":"before 1133–before October 1181","1133–1181":"1133–1181","1134–Male":"1134–Deceased","1155–1220":"1155–1220","1089–1130":"1089–1130","1118–1165":"1118–1165","1118":"1118","Aft 1165":"after 1165","Bef 1133":"before 1133","1134":"1134","1089":"1089","1155":"1155","1133":"1133","1165":"1165","1220":"1220","Bef October 1181":"before October 1181","1130":"1130","1181":"1181","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Marmion","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: perhaps an Anglicized form of an unidentified Gaelic name. Compare   Merriman  .","English (Lancashire; of Norman origin) and French: nickname from Old French <i>marmion</i> ‘monkey, brat’."],"variants":[{"name":"Merriman","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>mirie</i>, <i>merie</i>, <i>murie</i> ‘merry, pleasant’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’. Compare   Merry   1. This surname is established in Ireland (perhaps as an Anglicized form of an unidentified Gaelic name; compare   Marmion  ) as well as England.","there has probably been some confusion with <b>Marriman</b>, probably an occupational name meaning ‘servant of <i>Mary</i>’, from the female personal name <i>Mary</i> (see   Marie  ) + Middle English <i>man</i> in the sense ‘servant’, or perhaps a pet form of <i>Mary</i> using the hypocoristic suffix -<i>man</i>. The surname <i>Marriman</i> is now vanishingly rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Marmon","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Gloucestershire):","variant of   Marmion  .","variant of <b>Marriman</b>, an occupational name meaning ‘servant of Mary’, from the female personal name <i>Mary</i> (see   Marie  ) + Middle English <i>man</i> in the sense ‘servant’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Marmion 2nd Baron Marmion of Tamworth was born before 1133, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Roger Marmion Lord of Scrivesby and Tamworth, was 44 and his mother, Melisende de Rethel, was 14. He had at least 1 son. He died before October 1181, in Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Bef 1133–Bef October 1181":"enne 1133–enne oktoobrit 1181","1133–1181":"1133–1181","1134–Male":"1134–Surnud","1155–1220":"1155–1220","1089–1130":"1089–1130","1118–1165":"1118–1165","1118":"1118","Aft 1165":"pärast 1165","Bef 1133":"enne 1133","1134":"1134","1089":"1089","1155":"1155","1133":"1133","1165":"1165","1220":"1220","Bef October 1181":"enne oktoobrit 1181","1130":"1130","1181":"1181","O